Only conditions #5 and #8 met the criteria required to be used for the direct recycling of electrodes (Table 3
                     ), since no copper traces from the current collector were observed and the SBR was completely eliminated as shown in the TGA results in Fig. 3
                     (a) and (b); also, the recovery yield surpassed the 80 % value. The CMC signal remained intact, as it was not eliminated during this step. The elimination of the SBR was further confirmed by the lack of a decrease in the Weight (%) signal in the temperature ranges of 450–500 °C, where the SBR was expected to decompose. According to these results, a decrease of S/L ratio and an increase of H2SO4 concentration improve significantly graphite's purity, compared to temperature and time. To select one of these conditions as the most appropriate method for active material recovery, an LCA was carried out to compare the impact of each recycling condition of the DOE (Table 1) to the reference conditions set in the previous DOE (Table S1) [12].

For a complete validation of the optimized direct recycling protocol, cycled electrodes (GrC, 
                     Fig. 1 (c)) were recycled by applying the same conditions. For these EoL electrodes, the calcination step was performed before the leaching (Fig. 8 (a)
                     ) for safety reasons, due to the reactions that metallic lithium, which may be present in the electrodes, has in contact with water (GrC.CL). Fig. 8 (b) shows the TGA results of graphite materials obtained from calcinating and leaching production scraps and EoL electrodes (CL). After the leaching, no copper traces were observed, and the TGA performed showed no presence of SBR or CMC, proving that the investigated direct recycling protocol is valid for the elimination of the polymeric compounds in samples coming from production scraps and cycled cells, obtaining an efficiency value of almost 90 % in both Gr.CL and GrC.CL. The small bump at 550–600 °C observed has been associated in literature with the presence of LiOH, which was expected from the lithium salts from the electrolyte and SEI, and calcination of a small quantity of carbon black [6,39,40].
